{{distinguish|Saliba language (Papua New Guinea)}} {{Infobox language |name=Saliba |nativename= |states=[[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]] |speakers= 1,600 |date=1991–2008 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Piaroa–Saliban languages|Piaroa–Saliban]] |script=[[Latin script|Latin]] |iso3=slc |glotto=sali1298 |glottorefname=Saliba (Colombia) }} {{Expand French|Sáliva|date=May 2013}}
'''Saliba''' ({{lang-es|Sáliba}}, {{lang|es|Sáliva}}) is an indigenous language of [[Colombia|Eastern Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]].<ref name = "emeld">{{Cite web | title = E-MELD School of Best Practice: About Sáliba | work = E-MELD | accessdate = 2013-05-23 | date = 2005 | url = http://emeld.org/school/case/saliba/about.html }}</ref> Saliba was used by [[Jesuit]] [[missionaries]] in the 17th century to communicate with indigenous peoples of the [[Meta River|Meta]], [[Orinoco]], and [[Vichada River|Vichada]] valleys. An 1856 watercolor by [[Manuel María Paz Delgado|Manuel María Paz]] is an early depiction of the Saliva people in [[Casanare Province]].<ref>{{Cite web | last = Paz | first = Manuel María | authorlink = Manuel María Paz Delgado | title = Saliva Indian Women Making Cassava Bread, Province of Casanare | work = World Digital Library | accessdate = 2014-05-21 | url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/9017 }}</ref>
== Use == "Saliba was spoken by an ethnic group that lived along the central reaches of the [[Orinoco River]]."<ref>{{Cite web | title = A Study of the Saliba Language | work = [[World Digital Library]] | accessdate = 2013-05-23 | url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8992/ }}</ref>
"This language group was so isolated that the language was reported extinct in 1965."<ref name = "livingtongues">{{Cite web | last = Anderson | first = Gregory |author2=K. David Harrison | title = Language Hotspots - Northern South and Central America | work = Living Tongues Institute for Endangered Languages | accessdate = 2013-05-23 | date = 2007 | url = http://www.swarthmore.edu/SocSci/langhotspots/hotspots/NSA/ }}</ref> It is not being passed on to many children, but that practice is being reconsidered. As of 2007, "Sáliva speakers now are almost all bilingual in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and Sáliva children are only learning Spanish instead of their ancestral language."<ref name = "livingtongues"/>
As of 2007, "In the [[Orocue|Orocué]] area the language is only conserved to a high degree among elderly women; others understand Sáliba but no longer express themselves in the language."<ref name=e18/>
== Grammar == "Sáliba is an SOV language with noun classes and nominal classifiers. The language has a rich morphological system. In some cases, the realization of a verbal morpheme depends upon the form of the stem."<ref name = "emeld"/>
== Phonology == "Sáliba has a limited voicing distinction, and boasts six places of articulation for plosives. There are also two rhotics, and nasal counterparts for each of the five places of articulation for vowels."<ref name = "emeld"/>
